Durban - Police Minister Bheki Cele has praised detectives for uncovering millions of rands worth of drugs during an operation in Harding, south of KwaZulu-Natal, calling it the biggest drug haul in history. Cele, flanked by the national police commissioner, General  Khehla Sitole and other top brass visited the Hawks' offices in Port Shepstone on Thursday to inspect the drugs. This after a team made up of the Directorate for Priority Crime Investigation (Hawks), Crime Intelligence and Port Shepstone’s TRT and K9 searched a farm where they found a clandestine drug manufacturing laboratory. Two machines that are worth R1 million each were confiscated by police. Cele said the machines could produce 16 tablets in two seconds. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window.  While not yet confirmed, the drugs are believed to be Mandrax. Cele said the drugs were most likely shipped to other parts of the country and could range in price from R40 in Durban to R150 in Johannesburg. He said this was not the last of it as they were also planning to target another farm in Pietermaritzburg that was also believed to be producing drugs en masse.Cele said they knew the kingpin of the operation and would be pouncing on him soon. The value of the drugs had not yet been determined. Daily News